---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ReadingProgress from '../components/ReadingProgress.astro';

// The quantum-safe race: industry qubit trajectories toward the threshold at which a machine could
// break RSA-2048 (top), set against national migration deadlines (bottom), on one 2024-2040 axis.
// Qubit figures and targets are industry-stated; migration dates are the national instruments.
const YMIN = 2024;
const YMAX = 2040;
const X0 = 110;
const X1 = 690;
const x = (yr: number) => X0 + ((yr - YMIN) / (YMAX - YMIN)) * (X1 - X0);
const ticks = [2024, 2026, 2028, 2030, 2032, 2034, 2036, 2038, 2040];

// Top panel: physical qubits on a log scale.
const QT = 52; // y at 10^7
const QB = 248; // y at 10^0
const qy = (q: number) => QB - (Math.log10(q) / 7) * (QB - QT);
const decades = [
  { q: 10000000, t: '10M' }, { q: 1000000, t: '1M' }, { q: 100000, t: '100k' },
  { q: 10000, t: '10k' }, { q: 1000, t: '1k' }, { q: 100, t: '100' }, { q: 10, t: '10' },
];
// dLab is the demo-point label, tLab the stated target; ly/tly nudge those labels vertically and
// mx nudges the demo marker sideways, so the clustered low-qubit points do not collide.
const firms = [
  { demo: { yr: 2024, q: 105 }, dLab: 'Google Willow, 105 (2024)', ly: 6,
    target: { yr: 2029, q: 1000000 }, tLab: '1M by 2029', tly: -9 },
  { demo: { yr: 2024, q: 1121 }, dLab: 'IBM Condor, 1,121 (2023)', ly: -5,
    target: { yr: 2033, q: 100000 }, tLab: '100k by 2033', tly: -9 },
  { demo: { yr: 2025, q: 8 }, dLab: 'Microsoft Majorana 1, 8 (2025)', ly: -10 },
  { demo: { yr: 2025, q: 9 }, dLab: 'Amazon Ocelot, ~9 (2025)', mx: 16, ly: 18 },
];

// Bottom panel: national migration deadlines.
const R0 = 308;
const RH = 20;
const actors = [
  { name: 'Germany', body: 'BSI', marks: [2032], text: '2032', kind: 'hard', color: '#5b54a8' },
  { name: 'European Union', body: 'NIS CG', marks: [2035], text: '2035', kind: 'hard', color: '#5b54a8' },
  { name: 'United States', body: 'federal', marks: [2030, 2033], text: '2030, 2033 (federal)', kind: 'hard', color: '#2b4c7e' },
  { name: 'India', body: 'DST task force', marks: [2029, 2033], text: '2029 critical, 2033', kind: 'hard', color: '#6b7280' },
  { name: 'Thailand', body: 'NCSA QUANTA', marks: [2029, 2035], text: '2029 priority, 2035', kind: 'hard', color: '#2b4c7e' },
  { name: 'China', body: 'SM-series', marks: [], yr: 2038, text: 'no fixed date', kind: 'none', color: '#7a3b5e' },
];
---

<Base
  title="One shared core, many wrappers"
  description="A QSC Atlas commentary on the fragmentation of the post-quantum transition, and how it is governed through a network of expectations rather than a central authority."
>
  <ReadingProgress />
  <div class="container commentary">
    <p class="kicker">QSC Atlas commentary</p>
    <h1>One shared core, many wrappers</h1>
    <p class="standfirst prose">
      Why the post-quantum transition is fragmenting, and how it is governed all the same.
    </p>

    <p class="prose">
      One set of algorithms now sits underneath almost every national plan for post-quantum
      cryptography. When a United States federal agency published three standards in August 2024, a
      contested question became a settled technical fact, and within months those choices were in
      European certification catalogues, in national guidance from Paris to Bonn, and in the browsers
      shipping to the world. The core is shared. What surrounds it is not.
    </p>

    <h2>The wrappers: an instrument cascade</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The same algorithms arrive wrapped in very different instruments. In the European Union they are
      becoming binding through NIS2 and DORA and, from December 2027, the Cyber Resilience Act, though
      rarely by name. The obligation is carried by an undefined phrase, state of the art, whose
      cryptographic content is supplied by an interpretive layer of certification guidance that sits
      between legislation and practice. Elsewhere the same core is wrapped in soft national roadmaps,
      and across much of the world in nothing at all. What an organisation must do depends less on the
      mathematics, which is common, than on the jurisdiction it operates in, which is not. This is the
      instrument cascade: from an undefined legal standard down to a de facto migration obligation,
      with the operative rule written in the interpretive layer rather than the statute.
    </p>

    <h2>The clocks diverge, against an uncertain threat</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      The timetables fragment as sharply as the instruments, and every one of them is set against a
      threat that cannot be dated. Germany works to 2032; the European Union coordinates to 2035; the
      United States now sets 2030 and 2033 deadlines for its federal systems; India, more aggressive
      than any, wants its critical infrastructure quantum-safe by 2029 and the rest by 2033; Thailand's
      cyber agency runs a phased roadmap that completes in 2035; while China alone publishes no fixed
      national date. What each clock races is not an
      observed danger but an expectation. Climate governance can point to rising temperatures;
      quantum-safe governance has no such observable, only the qubit counts the industry says it will
      reach and an uncertain threshold at which they break today's encryption. The gap between the two
      is the whole risk: on its own roadmap one firm expects to cross that threshold around 2029, as
      early as the most aggressive migration deadline. The deadlines do their work anyway, because
      expectations are performative: they cascade vertically, a revised hardware estimate registering
      at once in Washington's gates and Brussels' milestones, and they align horizontally, as when
      four national agencies co-signed a single position in January 2024 that confined quantum key
      distribution to niche uses and named post-quantum migration the priority. Each national clock
      is, in the end, a wager that migration will finish before the machine arrives.
    </p>

    <figure class="race">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 452" role="img" aria-labelledby="r-t r-d" class="race-svg">
        <title id="r-t">The quantum-safe race: qubit trajectories against migration deadlines</title>
        <desc id="r-d">
          A single 2024 to 2040 timeline. Above, industry qubit targets rise toward the threshold at
          which a quantum computer could break RSA-2048, with one stated target reaching it around 2029.
          Below, national migration deadlines range from India's 2029 to Thailand's and the EU's 2035,
          while China alone sets none.
        </desc>

        {/* shared vertical gridlines + year labels */}
        {
          ticks.map((t) => (
            <g>
              <line x1={x(t)} y1="48" x2={x(t)} y2="418" class="race-grid" />
              <text x={x(t)} y="440" class="race-year" text-anchor="middle">{t}</text>
            </g>
          ))
        }
        {/* the 2030 marker, emphasised across both panels */}
        <line x1={x(2030)} y1="48" x2={x(2030)} y2="418" class="race-2030" />

        {/* ---- top panel: the quantum clock ---- */}
        <text x="8" y="24" class="race-panel">The quantum clock: where industry expects qubit counts to go</text>
        <rect x={X0} y={qy(10000000)} width={X1 - X0} height={qy(100000) - qy(10000000)} class="race-band" />
        <line x1={X0} y1={qy(1000000)} x2={X1} y2={qy(1000000)} class="race-crqc" />
        <text x={X1} y={qy(1000000) - 5} class="race-note" text-anchor="end">CRQC threshold (RSA-2048)</text>
        {
          decades.map((d) => (
            <g>
              <line x1={X0} y1={qy(d.q)} x2={X1} y2={qy(d.q)} class="race-grid faint" />
              <text x={X0 - 8} y={qy(d.q) + 3} class="race-axis" text-anchor="end">{d.t}</text>
            </g>
          ))
        }
        {
          firms.map((f) => (
            <g>
              {f.target && (
                <line x1={x(f.demo.yr)} y1={qy(f.demo.q)} x2={x(f.target.yr)} y2={qy(f.target.q)} class="race-traj" />
              )}
              <circle cx={x(f.demo.yr) + (f.mx || 0)} cy={qy(f.demo.q)} r="4.5" class="race-demo" />
              <text x={x(f.demo.yr) + (f.mx || 0) + 11} y={qy(f.demo.q) + 3 + (f.ly || 0)} class="race-label">{f.dLab}</text>
              {f.target && <circle cx={x(f.target.yr)} cy={qy(f.target.q)} r="5" class="race-target" />}
              {f.target && <text x={x(f.target.yr) + 9} y={qy(f.target.q) + 3 + (f.tly || 0)} class="race-label">{f.tLab}</text>}
            </g>
          ))
        }

        {/* ---- bottom panel: the migration race ---- */}
        <text x="8" y="286" class="race-panel">The migration race: when each actor must have crossed the line</text>
        {
          actors.map((a, i) => (
            <g>
              <text x="8" y={R0 + i * RH + 4} class="race-name">{a.name} &middot; {a.body}</text>
              {a.kind === 'none' ? (
                <g>
                  <line x1={x(2036)} y1={R0 + i * RH} x2={x(a.yr)} y2={R0 + i * RH} class="race-open" style={`stroke:${a.color}`} />
                  <polygon
                    points={`${x(a.yr)},${R0 + i * RH - 4} ${x(a.yr) + 9},${R0 + i * RH} ${x(a.yr)},${R0 + i * RH + 4}`}
                    style={`fill:${a.color}`}
                  />
                </g>
              ) : (
                <g>
                  {a.marks.length > 1 && (
                    <line x1={x(a.marks[0])} y1={R0 + i * RH} x2={x(a.marks[a.marks.length - 1])} y2={R0 + i * RH} class="race-span" style={`stroke:${a.color}`} />
                  )}
                  {a.marks.map((m) => (
                    <circle cx={x(m)} cy={R0 + i * RH} r="5" class="race-dot" style={`fill:${a.color}`} />
                  ))}
                </g>
              )}
              <text x={(a.kind === 'none' ? x(a.yr) : x(a.marks[a.marks.length - 1])) + 12} y={R0 + i * RH + 3} class="race-year2">{a.text}</text>
            </g>
          ))
        }
      </svg>
      <figcaption>
        The quantum-safe race. Above, where industry says its qubit counts are heading, against the
        threshold at which a machine could break RSA-2048; one stated target reaches it around 2029.
        Below, when each actor must have migrated: from India's 2029 for critical infrastructure to
        Thailand's and the EU's 2035, with the United States at 2030 and 2033 for federal systems,
        while China alone sets no fixed date. Qubit figures and targets are industry-stated; deadlines
        are the national instruments. Sources below.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>The failure mode is congestion, not absence</h2>
    <p class="prose">
      A network of expectations can fail, and its failure mode is congestion rather than a missing
      authority. The financial sector already faces DORA, national supervisors, G7 guidance and
      sectoral roadmaps at once, and the result is deferral: ENISA finds only a small share of European
      stakeholders have begun to migrate. The answer is not necessarily a central authority. It is to
      make the state of the transition common knowledge, who stands where, on which instrument, to what
      clock.
    </p>

    <p class="prose close">
      One shared core, many wrappers, held loosely together by a network of expectations. The Atlas
      maps the wrappers, country by country, so the fragmentation can at least be read.
    </p>

    <h2>Sources</h2>
    <ul class="sources">
      <li>NIST, FIPS 203, 204 and 205: post-quantum cryptography standards (August 2024).</li>
      <li>European Union: Directive (EU) 2022/2555 (NIS2); Regulation (EU) 2022/2554 (DORA); Regulation (EU) 2024/2847 (Cyber Resilience Act), applicable from December 2027.</li>
      <li>ENISA, European Union Agency for Cybersecurity: cryptographic certification (EUCC) and post-quantum readiness surveys (with ISACA).</li>
      <li>NIS Cooperation Group: A Coordinated Implementation Roadmap for the Transition to Post-Quantum Cryptography (2026), setting the 2030 and 2035 milestones.</li>
      <li>BSI (Germany): guidance on the migration to post-quantum cryptography.</li>
      <li>United States: NSA Commercial National Security Algorithm Suite 2.0 (CNSA 2.0), with 2030 and 2033 milestones for national security systems; Executive Order 14412 (2026) setting federal deadlines; and Executive Order 14306 (2025), which removed the earlier mandatory procurement requirement.</li>
      <li>India: Department of Science and Technology task force, Implementation of a Quantum-Safe Ecosystem in India (2026), targeting critical infrastructure by 2029 and full migration by 2033.</li>
      <li>Thailand: NCSA QUANTA post-quantum readiness platform (pqc-learn.ncsa.or.th), a phased advisory roadmap recommending the NIST standards, with high-priority systems migrated by 2028 to 2029 and national completion by 2035.</li>
      <li>China: OSCCA SM-series national cryptographic algorithms.</li>
      <li>Industry qubit figures and targets: IBM Quantum roadmap (Condor, 2023; about 100,000 qubits by 2033); Google Quantum AI roadmap (Willow, 2024; about 1,000,000 qubits); Microsoft (Majorana 1, 2025); Amazon (Ocelot, 2025).</li>
      <li>CRQC qubit-threshold estimate for RSA-2048: Gidney and Ekerå (2019); Gidney (2025).</li>
      <li>ANSSI, BSI, the Netherlands NLNCSA and the Swedish National Communications Security Authority: joint position paper on quantum key distribution (January 2024), prioritising post-quantum migration.</li>
      <li>Global Risk Institute and evolutionQ: Quantum Threat Timeline Report (2024), and Mosca's risk inequality (x + y &gt; z).</li>
      <li>G7 Cyber Expert Group: statement on quantum computing risks to the financial sector (2024).</li>
      <li>Bradford, A. (2020). The Brussels Effect. Oxford University Press.</li>
      <li>Budde, B., and Konrad, K. (2019). Tentative governing in a dynamic network of expectations. Research Policy (the governance of expectations).</li>
      <li>CEPS: Pupillo, L., et al. (2025). Strengthening the EU Transition to a Quantum-Safe World, Task Force report.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="attribution">
      A QSC Atlas commentary, drawing on the CEPS Task Force on Strengthening the EU Transition to a
      Quantum-Safe World (2025). <a href="/methodology">How the Atlas classifies countries &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .commentary {
    max-width: 44rem;
  }
  .kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-label);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-label);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
  }
  .commentary h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: var(--type-scene, 2rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-8);
  }
  .commentary h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-reading);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    margin: var(--space-10) 0 var(--space-3);
  }
  .commentary .prose + .prose {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }
  .close {
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .attribution {
    margin-top: var(--space-10);
    padding-top: var(--space-5);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .attribution a {
    color: var(--ink);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  /* The quantum-safe race figure */
  .race {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }
  .race-svg {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    display: block;
  }
  .race-grid {
    stroke: var(--hairline);
    stroke-width: 1;
  }
  .race-grid.faint {
    opacity: 0.5;
  }
  .race-2030 {
    stroke: var(--ink);
    stroke-width: 1;
    stroke-dasharray: 4 3;
    opacity: 0.55;
  }
  .race-band {
    fill: var(--ink);
    opacity: 0.05;
  }
  .race-conv {
    fill: var(--ink);
    opacity: 0.05;
  }
  .race-crqc {
    stroke: var(--ink);
    stroke-width: 1.5;
    stroke-dasharray: 2 2;
  }
  .race-traj {
    stroke: var(--ink);
    stroke-width: 1.5;
    stroke-dasharray: 5 3;
    opacity: 0.7;
  }
  .race-demo {
    fill: var(--ink);
  }
  .race-span {
    stroke-width: 2;
    opacity: 0.45;
  }
  .race-target {
    fill: var(--paper);
    stroke: var(--ink);
    stroke-width: 2;
  }
  .race-dot.is-soft {
    fill: var(--paper);
    stroke-width: 2;
  }
  .race-open {
    stroke-width: 1.5;
    stroke-dasharray: 4 3;
    opacity: 0.7;
  }
  .race-panel {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 11.5px;
    font-weight: 600;
    fill: var(--ink);
  }
  .race-axis,
  .race-year,
  .race-year2 {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 11px;
    fill: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .race-label,
  .race-note {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 10.5px;
    fill: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .race-name {
    font-family: var(--font-instrument);
    font-size: 11px;
    fill: var(--ink);
  }
  .race figcaption {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }

  /* Sources */
  .sources {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 0;
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--ink-muted);
  }
  .sources li {
    line-height: 1.45;
  }
</style>
